name: 1-ethylpiperazine-2,3-dione
Reason: The structure of 1-ethylpiperazine-2,3-dione includes several functional groups that influence its melting point: a piperazine ring, a ketone (two in this case due to the two carbonyl groups), and an ethyl group. Base structure for comparison, urea, has a melting point of approximately 133 °C, which can serve as a starting point since it presents similarity by containing two carbonyl groups as well. The piperazine ring has amine groups that can form hydrogen bonds, raising the melting point compared to hydrocarbons; we might estimate this increase to be about +20 °C. Each ketone typically lowers the melting point by a small amount due to the dipole-dipole interactions not being as strong as hydrogen bonds, let's estimate a lowering of -10 °C per ketone. The addition of an ethyl group would raise the melting point by approximately +5 °C due to increased molecular weight and van der Waals interactions. Considering urea's base melting point of 133 °C, after adjustments for piperazine, two ketones, and one ethyl group, the predicted melting point would be: 133 (base) + 20 (piperazine) - 10 (first ketone) - 10 (second ketone) + 5 (ethyl group) = 138 °C.
